metadata.name: The String #359
metadata.description:
|| Anniversary project for FX(hash) 1st birthday ||

Each virtual object consists of 365 lights.
Each light represents one day of the year.

We go through every single day, thinking it's all crucial. Yet, from a perspective, it all gets compressed into a single thread. Some of the events are brighter and more memorable. Others just blend or fade away.

I welcomed November 2021 with huge excitement and celebration. The joyful beginning of the month was followed by weeks of misery, anxiety, denial, and acceptance. It was a hard time, but in the long run, it was liberating and started a process of change. Change that happens dynamically to this day.

I couldn't join you last year, but I'm celebrating with you today!



In memory of my Dad.



Donations:
40% – Savepakistan - Flood Relief Fundraiser
10% – Three.js

metadata.name: Glossolalia #127
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Waves and Ripples #22
metadata.description:
Waves and Ripples is an implementation of a continuous CA, where wave like behaviours are obtained from the influence of neighbour cells over the cell itself. Depeding on the connections config for each cell, different patterns will emerge, creating waves, ripples, or a mix of both. When single loop is on, the calculations and drawings are done at once, which makes for a more chaotic visual.
Best enjoyed in full-screen :) 

Click anywhere to restart

Features : 
  shrinkFactor : 3 types
  connectArray: 16 possibilities,
  extraConnection: 4 types,
  mutualNeighbour: 40% chance,
  singleLoop: 30% chance
  monoChromo:  15% chance

Inspired by Matt Pearson's book.

metadata.name: NeuralFaces #889
metadata.description: NeuralFaces is an AI-driven avatar collection based on a neural network that was trained on face sketches. The latent vector for each face is generated from the transaction hash.

metadata.name: Urban Flora #133
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.name: Kinetograms #22
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.

metadata.name: Dump of Links. Part II #100
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork. It continues with the proposal of the first part, revealing remote points of hills full of abandoned URLs, with a contemplative approach.

A ‘404 button’ shines from above, in the distance, as if it were a star that -possibly- watches over. And below, in a metaphor for pollution, rise islands of floating garbage. As if it were a calm, lonely, suffocating breath, and even sometimes dangerously attractive.

Original sound of voice, piano & synths.

[ s ] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)
[ f ] -> fullscreen
[ q ] -> stop

Note: This artwork is an animated piece, and requires a powerful GPU for optimal real-time playback. It is important to note that it may not run properly on mobile devices, especially not high-end ones.

metadata.name: caravans #200
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by Paul Klee's 'Zwei Kamele und ein Esel' (Two camels and a donkey), abacuses and excessive shopping sprees.

An anonymous caravan makes its way through abstract deserts, carrying their semi-brutalist cargo towards an unknown destination.

All primary proceeds go to the Processing foundation.

Happy birthday fxhash!

Written in JavaScript, rendering to Canvas.

metadata.name: Blobby #489
metadata.description:
A sphere that has been contorted (or not) in various fashions! 

The spike level indicates how dense the protrusions are and the displacement level indicates how far these protrusions go. If any of those are 0, you'll get a flat sphere.

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #118
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: Flower Arrangement #47
metadata.description:
Flower arrangement made by code.

Possible features:
- Style: Natural, Oval, Triangular, Grassy
- Orientation: Square, Portrait, Landscape
- Palette: White, Cream, Tan, Pink, Green, Blue, Yellow, Orange
- Primary flower: Mix, Gerbera, Gerbera 2, Dahlia, Dahlia 2, Spiky, Unknown
- Primary color: Random, Light, Dark
- Secondary color: Random, Light, Dark
- Vase shape: Cylinder, Tumbler, Round, Curve
- Dish: true, false
- Table: true, false
- Texture: true, false

Live view options:
- Press "s" key: Saves the high resolution image (3300 x 3300 for square, 4200 x 3300 for portrait, 3300 x 4200 for landscape)

Depending on the device you run it on, it may take some time for the drawing to complete.
Best viewed in larger window size.
Made with p5js.

August 2022
ykxotkx
